      "id": 351729,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Carbocations, which contain a trivalent, positively charged carbon atom, react with water to give alcohols:</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBcE1RIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--164af3969387dafc125110d7605c49d8750a29d8/OChem_02_EC_023.jpg\" alt=\"A three-carbon chain with a carbocation at C2 reacts with water to form 2-propanol and a hydrogen ion.\">\n<p>How can you account for the fact that the following carbocation gives a mixture of <i>two</i> alcohols on reaction with water?</p>\n<img src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBcFFRIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--d24b11d7178826bf3459f7666c360b501ac67456/OChem_02_EC_024.jpg\" alt=\"In a reaction, a carbocation (a carbon cation bonded to a methyl group and an ethene group) reacts with water to form two alcohols.\">\n",
